04443nam a22006015i 9780822392897DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223928977 a10.1515/97808223928972doi  a(DE-B1597)553747  a(OCoLC)659520126  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aML3918.R37 7aSOC0430002bisacsh04a782.4216490899140731 aSharma, Nitasha Tamar, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHip Hop Desis :bSouth Asian Americans, Blackness, and a Global Race Consciousness /cNitasha Tamar Sharma; Josh Kun, Ronald Radano. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (366 p.) :b26 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRefiguring American Music00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Claiming Space, Making Race -- t1. Alternative Ethnics: Rotten Coconuts and Ethnic Hip Hop -- t2. Making Race: Desi Racial Identities, South Asian and Black Relations, and Racialized Hip Hop -- t3. Flipping the Gender Script: Gender and Sexuality in South Asian and Hip Hop America -- t4. The Appeal of Hip Hop, Ownership, and the Politics of Location -- t5. Sampling South Asians: Dual Flows of Appropriation and the Possibilities of Authenticity -- tConclusion: Turning Thoughts into Action through the Politics of Identification -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHip Hop Desis explores the aesthetics and politics of South Asian American (desi) hip hop artists. Nitasha Tamar Sharma argues that through their lives and lyrics, young "hip hop desis" express a global race consciousness that reflects both their sense of connection with Blacks as racialized minorities in the United States and their diasporic sensibility as part of a global community of South Asians. She emphasizes the role of appropriation and sampling in the ways that hip hop desis craft their identities, create art, and pursue social activism. Some desi artists produce what she calls "ethnic hip hop," incorporating South Asian languages, instruments, and immigrant themes. Through ethnic hip hop, artists, including KB, Sammy, and Deejay Bella, express "alternative desiness," challenging assumptions about their identities as South Asians, children of immigrants, minorities, and Americans. Hip hop desis also contest and seek to bridge perceived divisions between Blacks and South Asian Americans. By taking up themes considered irrelevant to many Asian Americans, desi performers, such as D'Lo, Chee Malabar of Himalayan Project, and Rawj of Feenom Circle, create a multiracial form of Black popular culture to fight racism and enact social change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aHip-hopxInfluence. 0aRap (Music)xSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aSouth Asian AmericansxMusicxSocial aspects. 0aSouth Asian AmericansxRace identity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh1 aKun, Josh, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRadano, Ronald, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822392897zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822392897423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822392897.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles